What this example covers:
1-  Deep copy for:
    1.1-  Primitives
    1.2-  Immutable objects (e.g., String)
    1.3-  Mutable objects (Date, List, custom Address class)
2-  Copy constructor
3-  Cloning (optional)
4-  Preventing side effects of shared references

Summary
-   Deep copy = full independence between original and clone.
-   Avoids bugs from shared mutable state.
-   Best used with copy constructors or serialization (for nested deep cloning).

ðŸ”¹ What Is Deep Copy?
A deep copy means creating a completely independent clone of an object along with all nested objects.
Any changes made to the copied object or its nested fields do not affect the original object.
In contrast, a shallow copy just copies references of nested objects (not their content).

ðŸ”¸ Why Deep Copy?
Needed when objects contain mutable nested objects
Avoids unexpected side effects (e.g., modifying one affects the other)
Used in cloning, caching, undo operations, etc.

ðŸ”„ Deep Copy vs Shallow Copy
| Aspect            | Shallow Copy                 | Deep Copy                                |
| ----------------- | ---------------------------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| Field Copying     | Copies object and references | Copies object **and** referenced objects |
| Nested Objects    | Still shared                 | New independent copies                   |
| Changes in Nested | Affects both                 | Doesnâ€™t affect the other                 |
| Complexity        | Simple                       | More complex                             |
